				<div class="row sub-section bg-grey">
					<div class="container">
						<div class="col-xs-12 col-sm-6">
							<h2>in summary&nbsp;</h2>
							<div class="h2-wrap">
								<div class="h2-helper">the brief</div>
							</div>
							<p>The Magic Toy Shop is a retailer of tyos, games and magic tricks, specialising in sourcing the most cherish items from everyone's childhood. It is based in Balmain, Sydney.</p>
							<p>The brief was to design a traditional, charming e-commerce site that replicates the service and feel of the shop.</p>
						</div>
						<div class="col-xs-12 col-sm-6">
							<h2>in summary&nbsp;</h2>
							<div class="h2-wrap">
								<div class="h2-helper">the solution</div>
							</div>
							<p>After conducting a competitive analysis, contextual inquiry in other toy shops, and user research, it became clear that the most important characteristics of the solution were delivering a Personal Experience and easy navigation.</p>
						</div>
						<div class="col-xs-12 bg-dark-grey">
							
						</div>
					</div>
				</div>
			</section>
			<section id="research" class="row">
				<div class="sub-section-heading">research</div>
				<div class="row sub-section bg-white">
					<div class="container">
						<div class="col-xs-12 col-sm-6">
							<h2>understanding the&nbsp;</h2>
							<div class="h2-wrap">
								<div class="h2-helper">competitive landscape</div>
							</div>
							<p>I have conducted an online competitive analysis between small boutique and large chain stores. The objective was to gain an understanding of how the brand positioning, information architecture, layout designs and search functions varied from site to site.</p>
							<p>Toy stores have flooded the online market. However, there is room for <i>The Magic Toy Store</i> to fill a niche in the vintage, more personalised toy market, as seen in the figure opposite.</p>
						</div>
						<div class="col-xs-12 col-sm-6">
							
						</div>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div class="row sub-section bg-grey">
					<div class="container">
						<div class="col-xs-12">
							<h2>understanding the&nbsp;</h2>
							<div class="h2-wrap">
								<div class="h2-helper">users</div>
							</div>
							<p>We were given the following personas from <i>The Magic Toy Shop</i>, which informed my design decisions throughout the project.</p>
						</div>
						<div class="col-xs-12 col-sm-4 persona-card">
							
						</div>
						<div class="col-xs-12 col-sm-4 persona-card">
							
						</div>
						<div class="col-xs-12 col-sm-4 persona-card">
							
						</div>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div class="row sub-section bg-light-blue">
					<div class="container">
						<div class="col-xs-12">
							<h2>card sorting and&nbsp;</h2>
							<div class="h2-wrap">
								<div class="h2-helper">information architecture</div>
							</div>
							<p>I conducted a cadr sorting exercise with 10 potential users to find out how to best organise the content on the website. The outcome was a set of categories and subcategories. The key insights I found from this was that people wanted to have a category with suggested toys, and to have the ability to search by brand and age.</p>
						</div>
					</div>
				</div>
			</section>
			<section id="iterative-design" class="row">
				<div class="sub-section-heading">iterative design</div>
				<div class="row sub-section bg-grey">
					<div class="container">
						<div class="col-xs-12">
							<h2>sitemaps and&nbsp;</h2>
							<div class="h2-wrap">
								<div class="h2-helper">user flows</div>
							</div>
							<p>After completing the card sorting exercise with potential users, I collated the results and formed the arrangement of the site (as reflected in the sitemap).</p>
							<p>I used the sitemap as a way to test the navigational experience of a user through the site.</p>
						</div>
